Problem:
A circular dartboard is divided into regions with various central angles, as shown. The probability of a dart randomly landing in a particular region is $\frac16$. What is the corresponding measure, in degrees, of the central angle of this section of the dartboard? [asy]
unitsize(1.5cm);
defaultpen(linewidth(.7pt));

pair O=(0,0);
draw(Circle(O,1));
draw(dir(0)--O--dir(90));
draw(dir(150)--O--dir(225));
[/asy]

Problem:
There are two colors Jessica can use to color this 2 by 2 grid. If non-overlapping regions that share a side cannot be the same color, how many possible ways are there for Jessica to color the grid?

[asy]
size(101);
draw(unitsquare);
draw((0,.5)--(1,.5));
draw((.5,0)--(.5,1));
label("$A$",(0,1),NW); label("$B$",(1,1),NE); label("$C$",(1,0),SE); label("$D$",(0,0),SW);
[/asy]

generated_answer:
Solution:
We can easily list out the possible colorings by brute force.  There are two choices for the top-left square, and two choices for the square to its right.  This determines the coloring of the entire square.

[asy]
unitsize(25);
draw(unitsquare);
draw((0,.5)--(1,.5));
draw((.5,0)--(.5,1));
label("A",(0,1),NW); label("B",(1,1),NE); label("C",(1,0),SE); label("D",(0,0),SW);
label("$1$",(0.25,0.75),N); label("$2$",(0.75,0.75),N);
label("$2$",(0.25,0.25),N); label("$1$",(0.75,0.25),N);
[/asy]

Thus, there are $\boxed{2}$ possible ways to color the grid.

Solution:
There are two choices for $A.$  Without loss of generality, assume $A$ is colored red.

[asy]
size(101);
draw(unitsquare);
fill((1,1)--(1,.5)--(.5,.5)--cycle,gray(.7));
draw((0,.5)--(1,.5));
draw((.5,0)--(.5,1));
label("$A$",(0,1),NW); label("$B$",(1,1),NE); label("$C$",(1,0),SE); label("$D$",(0,0),SW);
[/asy]

Then $B$ and $D$ must be colored blue.

[asy]
size(101);
draw(unitsquare);
fill((1,1)--(1,.5)--(.5,.5)--cycle,gray(.7));
draw((0,.5)--(1,.5));
draw((.5,0)--(.5,1));
fill((0,0)--(0,.5)--(.5,.5)--cycle,gray(.7));
label("$A$",(0,1),NW); label("$B$",(1,1),NE); label("$C$",(1,0),SE); label("$D$",(0,0),SW);
[/asy]

Finally, $C$ must be colored red.

[asy]
size(101);
draw(unitsquare);
fill((1,1)--(1,.5)--(.5,.5)--cycle,gray(.7));
draw((0,.5)--(1,.5));
draw((.5,0)--(.5,1));
fill((0,0)--(0,.5)--(.5,.5)--cycle,gray(.7));
fill((.5,.5)--(1,.5)--(1,0)--cycle,gray(.7));
label("$A$",(0,1),NW); label("$B$",(1,1),NE); label("$C$",(1,0),SE); label("$D$",(0,0),SW);
[/asy]

Therefore, there is only $\boxed{1}$ way to color the grid.

Solution:
Since $A$ and $C$ share an edge, they must be different colors.  Without loss of generality, let $A$ be red.  Then $B$ and $D$ must be different colors, so there are two cases.

[asy]
size(101);
draw(unitsquare);
draw((0,.5)--(1,.5));
draw((.5,0)--(.5,1));
label("$A$",(0,1),NW); label("$B$",(1,1),NE); label("$C$",(1,0),SE); label("$D$",(0,0),SW);
fill((0,1)--(0.5,1)--(0.5,0)--(0,0)--cycle,red);
[/asy]

In the first case, $B$ and $D$ must be different colors, so there are two possibilities.

[asy]
size(101);
draw(unitsquare);
draw((0,.5)--(1,.5));
draw((.5,0)--(.5,1));
label("$A$",(0,1),NW); label("$B$",(1,1),NE); label("$C$",(1,0),SE); label("$D$",(0,0),SW);
fill((0,1)--(0.5,1)--(0.5,0)--(0,0)--cycle,red);
fill((1,0)--(1,0.5)--(0.5,0.5)--(0.5,0)--cycle,green);
[/asy]

[asy]
size(101);
draw(unitsquare);
draw((0,.5)--(1,.5));
draw((.5,0)--(.5,1));
label("$A$",(0,1),NW); label("$B$",(1,1),NE); label("$C$",(1,0),SE); label("$D$",(0,0),SW);
fill((0,1)--(0.5,1)--(0.5,0)--(0,0)--cycle,red);
fill((1,0)--(1,0.5)--(0,0.5)--(0,0)--cycle,green);
[/asy]

In the second case, $B$ and $D$ must be the same color, so there is one possibility.

[asy]
size(101);
draw(unitsquare);
draw((0,.5)--(1,.5));
draw((.5,0)--(.5,1));
label("$A$",(0,1),NW); label("$B$",(1,1),NE); label("$C$",(1,0),SE); label("$D$",(0,0),SW);
fill((0,1)--(0.5,1)--(1,0.5)--(1,0)--(0,0)--cycle,red);
[/asy]

Therefore, there are $2+1=\boxed{3}$ ways to color the grid.

